    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm a bit stuck on a syntax tree for a sentence in my intro class. If I have the sentence \"The student saw the professor with the telescope,\" I'm seeing two different ways to parse the PP \"with the telescope.\" One version attaches it to the NP \"the professor,\" but my textbook shows it attaching to the VP \"saw.\" Can you explain the structural difference in how those branches are drawn and why the VP attachment is a valid reading?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The difference lies in where the Prepositional Phrase (PP) modifies. When the PP attaches to \"the professor\" (NP attachment), it functions adjectivally, describing *which* professor was seen. If it attaches to the VP \"saw\" (VP attachment), it functions adverbially, indicating *how* the seeing occurred, suggesting the student used the telescope to see. Both are grammatically valid, but they change the semantic focus of the sentence.",
      "source": "target",
