    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, thanks. So in the VP attachment version, the PP is essentially a constituent of the verb phrase. When you're actually drawing the tree, does that mean the PP node is a sister to the V and the NP, or is it nested differently? I'm having trouble visualizing the branching structure for that part.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the VP attachment structure, the PP is typically a sister to the VP's internal constituents, often branching off below the VP node, alongside the main verb (V) and its direct object (NP). You'll usually see the VP decompose into a head (V) and its complements/adjuncts, and the PP attaches as an adjunct to the VP. This means the PP modifies the entire action of the verb phrase, not just the noun phrase it's near.",
      "source": "target",
